  "body": "This code is in main branch right now:\r\n```\r\n    function setApprovalForAll(address operator, bool approved) public virtual override {\r\n        require(operator != _msgSender(), \"ERC721: approve to caller\");\r\n\r\n        _operatorApprovals[_msgSender()][operator] = approved;\r\n        emit ApprovalForAll(_msgSender(), operator, approved);\r\n    }\r\n```\r\nThis allows anyone with a Ether address to set a approver for themselves, even if they dont own a NFT here.\r\nIt is possible for a attacker to create a million accounts, and set approvers for them in a NFT , making gas costs for operations on this NFT very high.\r\n\r\nYes, the attacker needs to spend a lot of gas doing this, so it is not economical. This depends on the importance of the NFT.\r\n\r\nThis can be averted by simply checking the msgSender() has at least 1 NFT, \r\n```\r\n  require(_balances[_msgSender] > 0, \"Unknown owner\");\r\n```\r\nIf this is not a serious threat, maybe we can just put a comment here saying an attack is possible but not economical.\r\n\r\nOr perhaps there are other checks and balances I am aware of. I would like to know. Thanks!",
